Passport

Target IP: 192.168.242.112
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


Doing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.242.112 -p- returns the result shown in the image above. There are three TCP ports open on the target machine: FTP, SSH, and HTTP on their standard ports. Time to investigate these ports further.


Running the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.242.112 -p 21,22,80 returns the result shown in the image above. The scan detected anonymous login is not allowed for the FTP. Therefore, I will start my enumeration with the HTTP on port 80 first.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


I started a directory search using the command feroxbuster -u http://192.168.242.112 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x php,html,txt,css,js -d 4 --scan-dir-listings and obtained the result shown in the image above. What are these URLs with the http://192.168.242.112/acct_login/trace/*?


Reading through the http://192.168.242.112/acct_login/trace/51, I obtained the crucial information shown above. There are two hardcoded passwords: Serendipity1903@ and Mondo**********0123!, as shown in the image above. These passwords belong to the user luigi@passport.offsec.


The webpage above is returned for this web application on port 80. I pressed the Register Now button, but it didn't work. There is one more button with the label Reserved Area. Maybe this is the login interface?


Bingo! This is the login interface. However, I had zero luck trying to login using the two passwords. I tried performing SQL injections too, but I had no luck. From the port scan, there is one more application which I have not enumerated: FTP on port 21. Maybe I can test the credentials here?

Port 21: FTP

I gained access to the FTP application as the user luigi and the password Serendipity1903@, as shown in the picture above. I ran the command passiv before checking the directory listing as it was quite slow. Running the command ls -la shows there is one file ssh.bak, and a directory called uploads. I downloaded the ssh.bak using the command get ssh.bak on my machine. Inside the uploads directory, I was able to upload files too. However, from previous scan, it was unable to identify the uploaded files directory.

Exploitation

SSH Foothold as luigi via SSH Key


The ssh.bak contains the SSH private key, as shown in the image above.


To obtain the passphrase of the new SSH private key, I ran the command ssh2john id_rsa > hash. Then using the command john hash --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt, I managed to obtain the passphrase flowerpower. Afterwards, I changed the permission of the SSH key to 400 using the command chmod 400 id_rsa.


Then using the command ssh luigi@192.168.242.112 -i id_rsa, I managed to gain access to the target machine using the new SSH key of the user luigi. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user luigi.

Privilege Escalation & Flags

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: user luigi to user luca via SSH Key Access

Running the command sudo -l as the user luigi returns the result shown in the image above. The command /tmp/base64 /home/* can be executed with root privileges.


However, I noticed the base64 is missing from the /tmp directory. To fix this, I ran the command cp /usr/bin/base64 /tmp/. This just copies the base64 binary to /tmp directory, allowing me to run the command with root privileges. And bingo it worked successfully, as shown in the image above. Now I can try to read the files of the different users at /home/*.


When enumerating for sensitive files of the different users inside their home directories, I found the user 'luca' has their SSH key. Using the command sudo -u root /tmp/base64 /home/luca/.ssh/id_rsa, I was able to access their SSH key. Since this is encoded in base64, I will have to decode it before using it.


Using the command ssh2john luca_id_rsa > luca_hash, I obtained the passphrase hash set on the new SSH key belonging to the user luca. And to crack the passphrase hash, I ran the command john luca_hash --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt and successfully obtained the password dragonball as shown in the image above.

Vertical Privilege Escalation: user luca to user root via tmux Session Hijacking

Afterwards, I changed the permission of the new SSH key to 400 using the command chmod 400 luca_id_rsa. Then I connected to the target machine with this new SSH key using the command ssh luca@192.168.242.112 -i luca_id_rsa as the user luca.


Checking the .bash_history file, I notice this user runs the command tmux -S /RemoteOps attach -t rOps quite often. And running the same command, I was able to open a root shell as shown in the image above.


The two flags are shown in the image above.
